ype":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of Czech and Slovak <b>Beniš</b> (see   Benis  ), Sorbian <b>B'eniš</b> and <b>Bjeniš</b>, or of their Germanized form   Benisch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Benis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Russian Leonid, Mikhail, Vladimir.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): patronymic from the Yiddish male personal name <i>Benye</i> (a pet form of <i>Beniamin</i>; see   Bien  ,   Benjamin  ) + the Yiddish possessive and patronymic suffix <i>-s</i>.","Latvian: from a short form of the personal name <i>Benedikts</i> (see   Benedict  )."]}]},{"name":"Agatha","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Good, kind"],"variants":[]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":3,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible",